// DAY 4


Your task is to reverse an array of integers.

EX:
Input:
[1,2,3]
Output:
[3,2,1]

Java solution:
class Result {

    /*
     * Complete the 'reverseArray' function below.
     *
     * The function is expected to return an INTEGER_ARRAY.
     * The function accepts INTEGER_ARRAY a as parameter.
     */

    public static List<Integer> reverseArray(List<Integer> a) {
    // Write your code here
        List<Integer> lst= new ArrayList<>();
        for(int i=a.size()-1;i>=0;i--) {
            lst.add(a.get(i));
        }
        return lst;

    }
}

public class Solution {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        BufferedReader bufferedReader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
        BufferedWriter bufferedWriter = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter(System.getenv("OUTPUT_PATH")));

        int arrCount = Integer.parseInt(bufferedReader.readLine().trim());

        List<Integer> arr = Stream.of(bufferedReader.readLine().replaceAll("\\s+$", "").split(" "))
            .map(Integer::parseInt)
            .collect(toList());

        List<Integer> res = Result.reverseArray(arr);

        bufferedWriter.write(
            res.stream()
                .map(Object::toString)
                .collect(joining(" "))
            + "\n"
        );

        bufferedReader.close();
        bufferedWriter.close();
    }
}


My approach:

Mainly i picked to solve this problem because i was much familiar with reversing the numbers in array but not with arraylist. I iterated the arraylist from the end and added to the new arraylist
"lst" and finally returned it.
